ns as significant political actors during the interwar period. Ortiz's study reinterprets the political origins of the "Second" New Deal and Roosevelt's electoral triumph of 1936, adding depth not only to our understanding of these events and the political climate surrounding them, but to common perceptions of veterans and their organizations. In describing veteran politics and the competitive dynamics between the AL and the VFW, Ortiz details the rise of organized veterans as a powerful interest group in modern American politics.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNew Deal, 1933-1939. 0aProtest movementszWashington (D.C.)xHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxEducationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxGovernment policyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteransxPolitical activityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVeteranszUnited StatesxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xVeteranszUnited States. 7aHISTORY / Military / World War I.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aOrtiz.  aVFW.  abetween.  acompetitive.  adescribing.  adetails.  adynamics.  agroup.  ainterest.  amodern.  aorganized.  apolitics.  apowerful.  arise.  aveteran.  aveterans.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814762134.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814762561zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814762561/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA